<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create Item / Make Searchable Event Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Spawns collectible items, inventory items, weapons, ammo, mission objects, and searchable prim/object interactions.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Overview
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Create Item</Bold> and <Bold>Make Searchable</Bold> are related Event Points used for
        item and search interactions.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Create Item</Bold> spawns an item into the mission. These can be collectible rotating
        items that the player can pick up and add to inventory, such as guns, ammo, health, keys,
        grenades, or mission items. Some item types may be non-collectible or may have no obvious
        gameplay effect.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Make Searchable</Bold> does not create an item. Instead, it makes the nearest prim or
        object searchable. This is useful when you want the player to search objects, even if that
        particular object does not contain a reward.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_item_make_searchable_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important distinction:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Create Item can place a real item into the world or hide it inside a nearby prim.
                    Make Searchable only makes the nearest prim searchable; it does not create or hide an item by itself.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create Item Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Create Item</Bold> Event Point is used to spawn an item at the Event Point
        position, or optionally hide it inside the nearest prim/object depending on the selected
        flags.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Typical visible collectible items appear as rotating pickups in the world. When collected,
        they can be added to the player’s inventory or trigger other mission logic.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_item_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Adding a Create Item Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel, select <Bold>Create Item</Bold>, and click
        <Bold>OK</Bold>. The Edit EventPoint window opens with the normal common properties and the
        Create Item-specific fields.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_item_add_type.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Common Properties and Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Create Item uses standard Event Point common properties: index number, type, letter group,
        colour, position, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        If the item is meant to appear visibly in the world, place the Event Point where the pickup
        should appear. If the item is hidden in a prim, place the Event Point close to the prim/object
        that should become searchable and contain the item.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical placement detail:</Run>
                <Run>
                    When using Item Hidden in Prim, the item attaches to the nearest prim/object.
                    Place the Event Point close to the exact object you want the player to search.
                    If it is closer to the wrong prim, the wrong object may become searchable.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_item_position.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create Item Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Create Item has two main properties and two flags:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Item Type</Bold> — the item to spawn.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Count</Bold> — the quantity value, though it appears to be capped to one item in practice.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Item Follows Person</Bold> — appears to have no obvious effect.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Item Hidden in Prim</Bold> — hides the item in the nearest prim/object and makes that prim searchable.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_item_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Count
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Count</Bold> field is available, but testing suggests that only one item spawns per
        Event Point anyway. If you need multiple pickups, place multiple Create Item Event Points or
        copy/paste the item Event Point.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Treat Create Item as one item per Event Point. Do not rely on Count to spawn multiple copies unless you have tested that specific case in game.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Item Types
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Item Type field controls which item is spawned. Some are normal inventory pickups, some
        are weapons or ammo, some are mission objects, and some are special-case or dangerous.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_item_type_dropdown.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Keys
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Key / Gold Key</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Keys cannot normally be manually “used” by the player like a normal inventory action.
        However, collecting a key can still be used as a mission trigger. For example:
        <Bold>key collected → car is unlocked</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Guns, Weapons, and Ammo
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Pistol</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Shotgun</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>M16</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Grenades</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Shotgun Ammo</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Pistol Ammo</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>M16 Ammo</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Knife</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Baseball Bat</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Health and Utility
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Health</Bold> — health pickup.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Landmines</Bold> — appears to be non-collectible.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Mission or Miscellaneous Items
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Napkin</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Book</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>VHS Tape</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Floppy Disk</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Weed Away</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Explosives</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Inferno
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Inferno</Bold> is dangerous. Spawning this causes a large explosion and instant death.
        It should only be used deliberately, such as for a <Bold>Mission Lost</Bold> sequence or a
        scripted failure event.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Inferno warning:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Do not place Inferno as a normal pickup. It causes a large explosion and instant death.
                    Use it only when you intentionally want a failure/death sequence.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create Item Flags
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Item Follows Person</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        This flag appears to have no obvious effect in current testing. Treat it as uncertain or
        unused unless you have a specific tested use case.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Item Hidden in Prim</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        This flag hides the item inside the nearest prim/object. The nearest prim becomes searchable,
        and when the player searches it, the hidden item can be revealed.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,6,0,0">
        This is the correct option when you want the player to search an object and find a real item.
        For example, the player searches a bin, crate, desk, or other object and finds a key, tape,
        floppy disk, weapon, or mission item.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_item_hidden_in_prim.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Make Searchable Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Make Searchable</Bold> is a related Event Point. It has no type-specific properties.
        You place it on the map, and it attaches to the nearest prim/object, making that object
        searchable.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Unlike <Bold>Create Item</Bold> with <Bold>Item Hidden in Prim</Bold>, Make Searchable does
        not place an item inside the object. The nearest object becomes searchable, but nothing
        necessarily comes out of the search.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_make_searchable_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Use case:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Make Searchable is useful when you want the player to search multiple objects, with only one or some of them containing the real item.
                    It can create decoy searchable objects.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Create Item Hidden in Prim vs Make Searchable
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#555" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <StackPanel>
                <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" Margin="0,0,0,8">
                    <Run FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#9FE3A6">Create Item + Item Hidden in Prim:</Run>
                    <Run> nearest prim becomes searchable and contains the hidden item.</Run>
                </TextBlock>
                <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
                    <Run FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#9FE3A6">Make Searchable:</Run>
                    <Run> nearest prim becomes searchable but contains no item by itself.</Run>
                </TextBlock>
            </StackPanel>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        This distinction is important. Use <Bold>Create Item + Item Hidden in Prim</Bold> when there
        is an actual item to find. Use <Bold>Make Searchable</Bold> when you only want the object to
        be searchable, such as a decoy or part of a search puzzle.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        For items that should exist from the start of the mission, use:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Triggered By:</Bold> None / Game Starts.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Listening Mode:</Bold> Active.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        You can also place items behind other triggers if the item should only appear after a
        condition is met, such as an NPC being defeated, a counter being reached, a conversation
        finishing, or the player entering an area.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_item_trigger_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Practical Examples
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Visible Weapon Pickup</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create an item, choose <Bold>Shotgun</Bold>, place it in the world, and set it to trigger at
        mission start. The shotgun appears as a pickup.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Hidden Key in a Searchable Object</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create an item, choose <Bold>Gold Key</Bold>, enable <Bold>Item Hidden in Prim</Bold>, and
        place the Event Point near the object that should contain the key. The nearest prim becomes
        searchable and contains the key.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Search Puzzle with Decoys</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use <Bold>Make Searchable</Bold> on several nearby objects, then use one
        <Bold>Create Item</Bold> Event Point with <Bold>Item Hidden in Prim</Bold> for the real item.
        This lets the player search multiple objects before finding the correct one.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Mission Lost Explosion</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use <Bold>Inferno</Bold> only if you deliberately want to cause a large explosion and instant
        death, such as a scripted failure sequence.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Create Item Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>Create Item</Bold> and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose a letter group and colour that fits your mission organisation.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold> to place the item or place it near the prim it should be hidden in.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select the required <Bold>Item Type</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Count</Bold>, remembering that only one item appears to spawn in practice.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Enable <Bold>Item Hidden in Prim</Bold> only if the item should be found by searching the nearest object.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set trigger settings, usually <Bold>None / Game Starts</Bold> and <Bold>Active</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>OK</Bold>, save, and test the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Make Searchable Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>Make Searchable</Bold> and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place it near the prim/object that should become searchable.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set trigger settings, usually <Bold>None / Game Starts</Bold> and <Bold>Active</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>OK</Bold>, save, and test the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Remember that Make Searchable alone does not add an item to the object.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

</FlowDocument>
